An actinic keratosis is a rough, scaly patch of skin that forms from exposure to the sun for several years. It most often appears on the face, lips, ears, forearms, scalp, neck, or back of the hands. Also known as a solar keratosis, it grows slowly and usually first appears after a person is over 40 years old. You can reduce the risk of this skin condition by reducing sun exposure and protecting the skin from UV rays. If an actinic keratosis is left untreated, it may turn into a type of skin cancer called squamous cell carcinoma, with a probability of 5% to 10%.

Epithelioid sarcoma is a rare, slow-growing type of soft tissue cancer. Most cases begin in the soft tissue under the skin of the fingers, hand, forearm, lower leg or foot, although it can affect other areas of the body .Typically, epithelioid sarcoma begins as a small, solid growth or lump but is painless. It usually begins as a single developing formation, but multiple formations can occur over time while a person seeks treatment. Sometimes sarcomas appear as ulcers that do not accept treatment, and look like open wounds over the growing formations.

Basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer. Basal cell carcinoma begins in basal cells — a type of cell inside the skin that produces new skin cells instead of dying cells./nBasal cell carcinoma usually appears as a slightly transparent bump on the skin, although it can take other forms. Nevus basal cell carcinoma occurs most often on parts of the skin that are exposed to the sun, such as your head and neck. It is believed that the majority of nevus basal cell carcinomas are caused by prolonged exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun.

Seborrheic keratoses are common noncancerous skin growths. The risk of infection increases with age. Seborrheic keratoses usually appear brown, black, or light tan. The growths are waxy or scaly and slightly raised. The growths appear gradually, usually on the face, neck, chest or back. Seborrheic keratoses are harmless and non-contagious. This condition does not require treatment, but you can choose to get rid of it if it becomes irritated from contact with clothing or if its appearance bothers you.

It is a skin disease in which small, non-cancerous growths occur on the skin. The skin consists of several layers including the layer of fat cells, the epidermis, and the dermis. And this disease occurs in conjunction with the occurrence of abnormal growth in the dermis. It is very common and has nothing to do with skin cancer, and it is common for a person to develop this disease in more than one area of the body. It is painless, and has no negative health effects.

Melanoma, a risky type of skin cancer, arises from cells (melanomas) that convert the pigment melanin that gives your skin its colour. Melanoma can also affect your eyes and, rarely, parts of your body such as the inside of your nose or throat. Ultraviolet (UV) rays emitted from sunlight or ultraviolet (UV) rays. It may help you get UV rays. People under age 40, especially women, are more likely to develop melanoma. Skin cancer risk indicators can help ensure that precancerous changes are detected and treated before the cancer spreads. Successful treatment of melanoma is possible if the tumor is detected early.

Moles are a common type of skin growth condition. They often appear as small, dark brown spots and result from clusters of melanocytes. Moles generally appear during childhood and adolescence. Most people have about 10 to 40 moles, some of which may change appearance or disappear over time. Most moles are harmless. It rarely becomes cancerous. Monitoring moles and other pigmented spots is an important step in detecting skin cancer, especially malignant melanoma. The medical name for moles is nevus.

A bulging eye or eyes is usually caused by thyroid issues, such as Graves\' disease or hyperthyroidism. Symptoms include a gritty sensation with eye movement, eyelid swelling and redness and dry, irritated or watering eyes. Treatments include medications for thyroid disease, artificial tears, corticosteroids, immunosuppressant drugs and possibly surgery.
Strabismus (crossed eyes) is a condition in which one eye is turned in a direction that is different from the other eye. Treatment may include glasses, patching, eye exercises, medication or surgery.

Cataracts are the clouding of the lens of your eye, which is normally clear. Most cataracts develop slowly over time, causing symptoms such as blurry vision. Cataracts can be surgically removed through an outpatient procedure that restores vision in nearly everyone.

People with uveitis develop red, swollen, inflamed eyes. They also have eye pain. Certain conditions increase the risk of uveitis, but the disease often occurs for no known reason. Treatments can restore lost vision and prevent further vision loss. Certain types of uveitis can return after treatment. Untreated uveitis can lead to blindness.

People with glaucoma have optic nerve damage from fluid buildup in the eye. Left untreated, this eye pressure can permanently affect vision. Glaucoma is the second leading cause of blindness in the world. Treatments — including eyedrops, laser treatments and surgeries — can slow down vision loss and save your sight.
